This is what my job looks like on the outside. Behind the scenes, our team in Business Development for Cascade Health support Providers and Referral sources with information and education, analyze metrics and stats that measure market share, quality and patient and family feedback, respond to communication or care challenges, provide reporting of market trends and celebrate our Clinical Team Members that make the highest quality care in Lane County possible. It's a high honor to work for a local, non-profit healthcare provider that offers best practices in every service line and that is recommended by so many in our community. Business Development Professionals are responsible for identifying and developing new business opportunities for a company. Our work also includes: Identifying new business opportunities: Researching potential clients and markets, and developing strategies to identify new business opportunities Developing marketing and sales strategies: Creating strategies to help grow a company's business Developing client relationships: Maintaining client relationships and negotiating contract terms Collaborating with Clinical teams: Working with Clinical teams to develop proposals and convert leads into customers Making presentations: Giving presentations to prospective clients and internal executives Creating processes and policies: Developing and implementing processes and policies to support the business Monitoring projects: Ensuring that contracts are executed as agreed Gathering customer and competitor data: Collecting information from customers and competitors Forming partnerships: Helping to form strategic alliances, joint ventures, or collaborations Product development: Conducting market research and gathering customer feedback to drive innovation When we see each other in the community, I may be representing 1 Cascade Health program or all of them. I'll probably be taking some notes to follow-up on later and scheduling our next meeting. It may be a heavy or difficult meeting, but sometimes, they get to look like this! Unfortunately, there’s no denying that a sales role can often carry a negative connotation. So when I accepted my current job, I found myself a little reluctant with sharing my title to others. Why? Because for me, this “sales” role is not at all about meeting a quota or pushing services on people. This role is about ensuring every person in this country receives the highest quality of healthcare they deserve and have worked so hard for. But that level of care isn’t received if there aren't enough people to take care of them. Now, your mind may be wandering to the shortages of physicians and nurses. And while they’re a large piece of the puzzle, there’s a heck of a lot more people working behind the scenes to also deliver care to patients. Ghosted emails and quick phone drops - yes, they can be disheartening. But that's because I care and know what we [ Medasource ] have to offer; and man is it essential. So, instead of telling people my actual job title right off the bat, I first explain to them that I make sure health systems have all the right people, in the right place, at the right time, to provide the highest quality of care to their patients. Cheers to “selling” healthcare solutions that undoubtedly make a positive difference in so many lives. #healthcare #sales #purposedriven

From the Rebel's Guide to Health IT Sales: Tip #2 You’ve done your research—now it’s time to rethink your approach. In Health IT sales, the instinct is to go straight to the top, targeting the CIO. But here’s the real deal: That path often leads to a dead end. 😎 Rebel Tip: Begin with the department leader most impacted by your solution. Build a genuine connection with them first. The right advocate can turn obstacles into opportunities, opening doors you didn’t even know existed. Their influence can accelerate your sales cycle and ensure your solution gets the attention it truly deserves. Consider this insight from a Healthcare CIO (full quote in The Rebel's Guide): ❝ CIOs are often where the answer is ‘No’ because it seems like it's competing with the technology portfolio.
